# Wikipedia page: "History of Linux" — kernel releases, licensing debates, distribution forks, credit disputes
{"eventId":"evt_linux_001","eventType":"claim_first_seen","claimId":"clm_linux_001","fromRevisionId":1280000601,"toRevisionId":1280000602,"section":"Creation","before":"","after":"Linux was created by Finnish computer science student Linus Torvalds, who first announced the project on August 25, 1991, in a Usenet posting to the comp.os.minix newsgroup. The initial announcement described it as 'a (free) operating system (just a hobby, won't be big and professional like gnu)' for 386(486) AT clones.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The Usenet announcement claim and the famous 'just a hobby' quote first appeared in this revision.","detail":"The Usenet post (Message-ID: 1991Aug25.205708.9541@klaava.Helsinki.FI) is archived at Google Groups and widely cited as the founding document of the Linux project."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Established the canonical origin narrative with the recognized founding date and quotation.","confidence":0.96,"discussionType":"origin_claim"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-01-20T11:15:30Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_linux_002","eventType":"claim_reworded","claimId":"clm_linux_002","fromRevisionId":1280000603,"toRevisionId":1280000604,"section":"Creation","before":"Linux was originally developed as a terminal emulator and later evolved into a full operating system kernel.","after":"Linux began as a terminal emulator that Torvalds wrote to access the University of Helsinki's Unix servers from his personal computer. It relied on Minix for development tooling and the GNU C Compiler (GCC) for compilation. By October 1991, version 0.02 was released with the ability to run bash and GCC itself — achieving a self-hosting development environment where Linux could compile its own source code.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The claim was expanded from a vague 'terminal emulator later evolved' to a specific toolchain narrative (Minix host, GCC compiler, bash shell).","detail":"Edition 0.02's self-hosting capability (compiling itself) is widely regarded as a critical inflection point — it transformed Linux from a dependent project to a self-sustaining one."},{"fact":"The self-hosting milestone and version 0.02 details were added.","detail":"Source: Torvalds' 1991 release notes for Linux 0.02, which explicitly note the self-compilation capability."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Enhanced the origin story from a vague evolution narrative to a specific technical milestone with toolchain documentation.","confidence":0.92,"discussionType":"historical_accuracy"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-02-28T09:30:45Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_linux_003","eventType":"talk_thread_opened","claimId":null,"fromRevisionId":1280000605,"toRevisionId":1280000606,"section":"Talk:History of Linux","before":"","after":"Credit attribution: The article's naming section currently attributes the name 'Linux' to Ari Lemmke, the FTP administrator who named the directory 'linux' on ftp.funet.fi. However, Torvalds has stated that he originally wanted to call the project 'Freax' (a portmanteau of 'free,' 'freak,' and 'Unix') and that Lemmke independently chose 'Linux' without consulting him. Both accounts are documented in Torvalds' autobiography 'Just for Fun' (2001). Should both versions be presented, or is the Lemmke attribution sufficient?","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"A new talk page thread titled 'Naming dispute: Freax vs. Linux attribution' was opened.","detail":"Started by user KernelHistorian on 2024-03-15T16:20:33Z."},{"fact":"The thread identifies conflicting accounts: the commonly told story (Lemmke named it) vs. Torvalds' own account that adds the rejected 'Freax' name.","detail":"Both accounts are cited to Torvalds' autobiography, creating a self-contradiction narrative."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Opened a dispute about whether the naming narrative should include Torvalds' rejected alternative name for fuller historical context.","confidence":0.71,"discussionType":"credit_attribution"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-03-15T16:20:33Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_linux_004","eventType":"citation_replaced","claimId":"clm_linux_003","fromRevisionId":1280000607,"toRevisionId":1280000608,"section":"Licensing","before":"In 1992, Torvalds switched Linux's license to the GNU General Public License (GPL) version 2, enabling its combination with GNU userspace components to form a complete free operating system. [21]","after":"Linux was initially released under a custom license prohibiting commercial distribution. In January 1992, Torvalds switched to the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2), a decision he later described as 'the best thing I ever did.' The switch enabled the combination of the Linux kernel with the GNU Project's userspace components (compiler, shell, core utilities) to form a complete free operating system — a combination that the GNU Project later advocated describing as 'GNU/Linux.' The license change is recorded in the release notes for Linux 0.12. [21][35]","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"New citation [35] was added: the Linux 0.12 release notes (January 1992) containing the license change notice.","detail":"This is the primary-source documentation of the GPL switch, replacing a secondary-source paraphrase."},{"fact":"The initial commercial-restriction license and the GNU/Linux naming advocacy were added to the claim.","detail":"Both are historically significant: the initial non-commercial restriction explains why the GPL switch was consequential, and the GNU/Linux naming debate is a recurring topic in Linux history."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Enhanced the licensing-claim with primary-source documentation, the pre-GPL license context, and acknowledgment of the GNU/Linux naming controversy.","confidence":0.91,"policyDimension":"verifiability","discussionType":"citation_strengthening"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-04-22T14:10:55Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_linux_005","eventType":"section_reorganized","claimId":null,"fromRevisionId":1280000609,"toRevisionId":1280000610,"section":"Development model","before":"(Section mixed kernel release history, corporate involvement, and community governance in an unstructured chronology)","after":"(Section split into: 'The cathedral and the bazaar: distributed development model', 'Corporate participation (1999-present): IBM, Red Hat, Google, Microsoft', 'Release cycle and version numbering (1.0, 2.0, 2.4, 2.6, 3.x, 4.x, 5.x, 6.x)')","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The Development model section was restructured into three thematic subheadings: development philosophy, corporate participation, and release history.","detail":"The 'cathedral and bazaar' heading references Eric Raymond's 1999 essay, which documented and popularized Linux's development model."},{"fact":"Corporate participation was expanded to include Microsoft, reflecting the significant shift from Microsoft's historical opposition to Linux (Steve Ballmer's 2001 'cancer' comment) to its embrace (Azure Linux usage exceeding Windows Server in 2024).","detail":"This represents a major narrative arc in Linux history that the previous version did not capture."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Restructured a chronologically confused section into a thematically organized account of development philosophy, corporate evolution, and release history.","confidence":0.84,"discussionType":"structure_dispute"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-05-30T11:45:20Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_linux_006","eventType":"revert_detected","claimId":"clm_linux_004","fromRevisionId":1280000611,"toRevisionId":1280000612,"section":"GNU/Linux naming controversy","before":"The Free Software Foundation and the GNU Project advocate referring to the operating system as 'GNU/Linux' or 'GNU+Linux' to acknowledge the GNU Project's contribution of essential userspace components. This naming is controversial, with many developers and the majority of media outlets referring to the system simply as 'Linux.'","after":"The Free Software Foundation and the GNU Project advocate referring to the operating system as 'GNU/Linux' or 'GNU+Linux' to acknowledge the GNU Project's contribution of essential userspace components. This naming is controversial, with many developers and the majority of media outlets referring to the system simply as 'Linux.'","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"Revision 1280000611 was an exact revert of revision 1280000610.","detail":"An editor had replaced the balanced paragraph with 'Richard Stallman's fanatical insistence on calling it GNU/Linux is an exercise in credit-hogging. The GNU tools are replaceable components; the kernel is the OS. The 'GNU/Linux' label is propaganda, not history.' The revert was applied by moderator NeutralTechEditor with summary: 'rv — WP:BLP and WP:NPOV apply even to naming controversies. The existing text attributes both positions without endorsing either.'"}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Restored neutral dual-position presentation after a screed against the GNU/Linux naming convention was inserted in wiki voice.","confidence":0.97,"policyDimension":"neutrality","discussionType":"edit_revert"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-07-10T15:55:30Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_linux_007","eventType":"claim_strengthened","claimId":"clm_linux_005","fromRevisionId":1280000613,"toRevisionId":1280000614,"section":"Adoption","before":"Linux has become widely adopted in server infrastructure, powering the majority of web servers, cloud computing platforms, and supercomputers.","after":"As of 2024, Linux runs on: 96.3% of the world's top one million web servers (Netcraft survey), 100% of the TOP500 supercomputers (a milestone first reached in 2017 and maintained every year since), approximately 90% of public cloud workload instances (Flexera 2024 State of the Cloud Report), and all Android devices (over 3 billion active devices globally per Google). Linux-based operating systems also power the majority of embedded systems, network routers, IoT devices, and in-vehicle infotainment systems.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The claim was expanded from a vague 'majority' estimate to specific percentages with named survey sources.","detail":"Each percentage is sourced to a specific survey: Netcraft (web servers), TOP500 (supercomputers), Flexera (cloud), Google (Android)."},{"fact":"Additional deployment domains were added: embedded systems, network routers, IoT, automotive infotainment.","detail":"This reflects Linux's position as the dominant general-purpose kernel across virtually all computing domains except desktop."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Transformed a qualitative adoption claim into a domain-by-domain quantified assessment with named survey sources.","confidence":0.89,"discussionType":"data_update"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-08-15T10:30:45Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_linux_008","eventType":"section_reorganized","claimId":null,"fromRevisionId":1280000615,"toRevisionId":1280000616,"section":"Regulation and security","before":"(Section focused on individual CVEs and vulnerability timelines without narrative structure)","after":"(Section reorganized into: 'The vulnerability disclosure debate (full disclosure vs. coordinated disclosure)', 'Supply chain security (xz backdoor incident, 2024)', 'Government security requirements (FedRAMP, Common Criteria, EU Cyber Resilience Act)')","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The vulnerability-list section was restructured into a thematic framework covering disclosure policy, supply chain incidents, and government compliance.","detail":"The reorganization was prompted by the 2024 xz backdoor incident, which editors felt required a structural home that the previous CVE-list format couldn't provide."},{"fact":"The EU Cyber Resilience Act was added to the government-requirements subheading, reflecting its 2024 finalization and its implications for open-source software.","detail":"The CRA's liability provisions for open-source maintainers have been a major topic of discussion in the Linux community."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Replaced a CVE laundry list with a thematically organized security-governance framework reflecting contemporary policy debates.","confidence":0.82,"discussionType":"structure_dispute"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-10-05T09:20:35Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_linux_009","eventType":"talk_reply_added","claimId":null,"fromRevisionId":1280000617,"toRevisionId":1280000618,"section":"Talk:History of Linux","before":"(Existing thread on 'Naming dispute: Freax vs. Linux attribution')","after":"I've drafted a revised naming subsection that presents both accounts: 'The kernel was originally named 'Linux' by Ari Lemmke, the FTP site administrator who created the directory on ftp.funet.fi without consulting Torvalds. Torvalds had originally considered the name 'Freax' (a portmanteau of free, freak, and the -x suffix common in Unix names) and had even used it for local files, but later stated that he is glad the name was changed.' This presents both versions as documented facts rather than resolving the apparent contradiction into a single canonical narrative.","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"A proposed revised naming subsection was posted to the thread.","detail":"Posted by user KernelHistorian on 2024-11-08T18:15:40Z."},{"fact":"The proposed text presents both the Lemmke and Freax accounts as documented facts without attempting to synthesize them into a single narrative.","detail":"This approach follows Wikipedia precedent for handling conflicting historical accounts: present both verifiably, do not adjudicate between them."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Proposed resolution for the naming dispute: present both documented accounts as parallel facts rather than synthesizing a single canon.","confidence":0.79,"discussionType":"dispute_resolution"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-11-08T18:15:40Z"}
{"eventId":"evt_linux_010","eventType":"talk_thread_archived","claimId":null,"fromRevisionId":1280000619,"toRevisionId":1280000620,"section":"Talk:History of Linux","before":"(Active thread: 'Naming dispute: Freax vs. Linux attribution' with 22 replies over 8 months)","after":"(Thread resolved. The naming subsection now presents both the Lemmke and Torvalds accounts as parallel documented facts without adjudicating between them. The contradictory accounts are presented in consecutive sentences with citations to Torvalds' autobiography for both.)","deterministicFacts":[{"fact":"The naming dispute thread was resolved with the parallel-account framing adopted.","detail":"The closing editor noted that a 22-reply thread over 8 months on a historical footnote was 'one of the more intense naming disputes' they had seen, exceeding even the 'GNU/Linux' thread's initial activity."}],"modelInterpretation":{"semanticChange":"Resolved a naming-origin dispute by presenting contradictory accounts as parallel documented facts — a technique that preserves both verifiability and neutrality.","confidence":0.81,"discussionType":"dispute_resolution"},"layer":"observed","timestamp":"2024-12-15T11:00:00Z"}
